Accident Description:
At around 8:00 p.m. a fire broke out on a zirconium pickle line at a metal fabrication plant. The operator launched the internal emergency plan. 12 employees were evacuated. Staff and the fire brigade fought the fire with a foam nozzle. By 9:00 p.m. the fire had been put out and the internal emergency plan was lifted at 9:45 p.m.
 ;
The two investigations carried out by the operator did not definitively establish the cause of the fire. The first hypothesis would be an ignition of electrical origin; the suspected equipment is a pump motor and its electrical connection socket. The second hypothesis would be ignition linked to the presence of zirconium; the satin finish generates zirconium fines, the spontaneous ignition of which in the open air is possible.
 ;
The fact that the packed tower scrubber did not stop extracting fumes despite the emergency shutdown of the machine was undoubtedly an aggravating factor in the accident.

Causes of the accident:
The accident occurred shortly before the end of a shift, scheduled for 3.00 p.m., during the incineration of explosive materials. To date, the company has not been able to identify sufficiently precisely what might have caused the ignition of the material and the resulting explosion.
Based on the initial analyses carried out, and following the observations made by the inspection panel established by the Regional Technical Committee (CTR) to conduct an extraordinary inspection following the accident, the company decided to take action in relation to the following potential problem areas that it had identified:

procedural arrangements, particularly the operating procedure for moving and incinerating materials;
training for staff members and supervision by those in leadership roles;
the recording and traceability of materials leaving a work area and entering room 80, where the static furnace is located;
introducing CCTV monitoring, including so as to be able to objectively reconstruct the lead-up to accidents and near misses;
more careful management of access to the plant.

The direct cause was corrosion under insulation in a 4” pipe between av naphta pump and a cooler. The indirect cause was that this pipe had fallen out of the inspection system SAP in 2008, and therefore had not been inspected since. ;
 ;
 ;

Lesson Learned:
Plant/Equipment: Corrosion of piping under insulation due to lack of inspection
Organisational/ system related: ;
- The system did not assertain that that all essential equipment/ piping was included in the inspection and maintenance programme.
- The risk assessment did not evaluate the need for fire- and gas detection in the pipestill area. Had there not been personnel present, the leakage might not be identified in time to prevent an ignition.
Human: The safety of involved operations- and maintenance personnel was nut sufficient during this situation. In the early phase of the situation 3 operators were close to the point of leakage in order to identify the leakage point. They did not carry with them the neccessary HC-gasdetector nor protection against benzen-exposure. This was not according to internal procedures. ;

Causes of the accident:
Self ignition of filters in the turbine. The self ignition was probably caused by accumulation of biomass (mainly insects) in the air inlet filters. This accumulation caused too high temperatures in the filters over a long period of time, and has probably also caused a change in the self ignition temperature of the hotoil.
The ; company report states that the incident was not caused by a single technical or human error, but was a result of several direct and underlying causes: design, decisions, operational practices, organisational conditions, conditions related to training, management and control, which together resulted in extensive damage to the plant. The direct cause of the fire was auto-ignition of the filters in the air intake of gas turbine generator no. 4 (GTG4), due to temperatures that were much too high over a long period of time. The underlying cause of the fire was the fact that the anti-ice heat exchanger was used outside its intended area of use, causing this high temperature. The high temperature in the filter housing was not detected.
 ;

Lesson Learned:
A wide rage of lessons learned were identified related to:

emergency response management, ;
organisation, management and governance
Work processes, requirements and barriers ;
Technical design and improvements
emergency preparedness.
 ;
 ;
 ;

Following the accident, the operator put in place the following measures:

the low temperature sensor in the bund was moved closer to the outlet of the overflow valve;
the high filling level and very high filling level of the storage tank were checked and redefined;
the settings of the storage tank’s very high level alarm were changed and its high level alarm was turned on, having previously been off;
a procedure for using the ejectors was drafted;
the monitoring teams’ parameters for monitoring the production and filling levels of the storage tanks were redefined.

Causes of the accident:
The storage tank was being prepared for maintenance. The cover of the manhole on the roof had been loosened and the support legs had been retracted to the working position. The roof’s drain valve had been closed in preparation for the storm (the storage tank had not yet been modernised so its drain system was vulnerable and there was a risk that, in the event of a leak, run-off would escape into the site’s wastewater treatment plant). There were procedures in place specifying how these steps should be taken. The stormwater that accumulated (around 67 ;m³) caused the roof to sink and gasoline to rise up through the loosened manhole cover. The next day, the operator did not refer to gasoline rising up from the tank and presented a number of theories:

a puddle may have gone undetected the previous day following pumping, as the area had been inspected at night with self-contained breathing apparatus being worn;
leaking drain (an expert inspection was carried out during maintenance of the storage tank);
blocked roof, but no movement in the storage tank had been noted.

Lesson Learned:
Following the accident, the operator put in place the following remedial measures:

disciplinary interview for those who failed to comply with the isolation procedure;
improving the isolation/lockout procedure, in particular the risk assessment process for liquid isolation;
training on instructions and isolation, with a particular focus on liquid isolation and electrical isolation;
drawing up alarm management procedures.

The operator took several corrective measures:



controlling the variation in arc voltage to stop melting as soon as secondary arcing occurs;
cutting off the stinger cooling water in the event of an abnormal variation in water flow;
improving training and methods of receiving and checking components related to stub/stinger assembly, by implementing compliance reports, component tracking sheets and reinforcement of procedures;
a review of the hazard assessment and sharing lessons learned with the whole profession.

The remedial action concentrated on improving the checklists:

by including warning and information points for operatives, incorporating the main safety points (limitation) and explaining the background to these points;
by specifying whether they involve equipment that could give rise to serious scenarios;
by ensuring a process of validation by the process safety service, in particular for the equipment that could give rise to scenarios taken into account in the technology risk management plans (plans de prévention des risques technologiques - PPRT).

Causes of the accident:
Direct cause – wrong material in replacement valve. ;
Root cause – lack of formal routines to safeguard correct material properties.

 ;

Lesson Learned:
The main lessons learned from the incident was as follows; the technical standard around the system was ready for an upgrade, the competence and understanding of the operators, especially concerning important alarms needed a refresher, the communication between different parts in the organization was not optimal.
Based on this, a technical upgrade of the system is being performed, amongst other replacement of leaking valves. Regarding competence and understanding, there is now an increased focus on strenghtening of communication lines and risk assessments.
